Steven Wendell Isaacs (born June 19, 1969) is an American actor, creative director and musician, perhaps best known as the lead vocalist for the bands The Panic Channel, featuring former members of Jane's Addiction, and Skycycle, as well as being a VJ for MTV from 1991 to 1993.
In 1989, Isaacs attended Musicians Institute in Hollywood, California, where he studied guitar.
In late 1990, he left the Mad Hatter's Espresso Bar to host the open mike at Highland Grounds Café in Hollywood.
He became an MTV VJ in September 1991, which required relocating from Los Angeles to New York City.
Isaacs left MTV in April 1993.

Isaacs toured with the show from 1993 to January 1995, performing over 500 shows in 32 cities in the U.S., including a show for President Bill Clinton at the Kennedy Center, and receiving a 1995 Helen Hayes Awards Outstanding Lead Actor nomination for his performance at that Washington DC venue.

From 2007–2010, Isaacs acted as Creative Director at Deep Focus NYC, an interactive marketing and advertising agency specializing in social media.
His 2009 campaign for HBO's Flight of the Conchords won two Webby Awards and creative directed the Mad Men viral microsite, Mad Men Yourself.
In June 2013, Isaacs launched the web series Sweet Ride USA, acting as host, executive producer and creative director.
